pr_title: feat: Adding a relay bot for matrix<>qaul bridge
pr_body:
Raising the PR so we can do smooth code review for the code which we will be updating into the matrix-bridge branch.
As per the current state state
1. Run the bridge client `cargo run --bin=qaul-matrix-bridge`
2. Invite user `@qaul-bot` to any of the matrix rooms.
3. In message send `!qaul` and it will respond.

[{'comment_id': 1205079195, 'comment_body': 'The name should be more explanatory, e.g. `qaul-bridge` or `qaul-matrix-bridge`. IMHO `qaul-matrix-bridge` would be best, as it is the most self-explanatory.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 5, 25, 7, 0, 51, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MathJud', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1205080882, 'comment_body': 'Please write a specific README for the binary, that explains what the binary does and how to start it.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 5, 25, 7, 2, 21, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MathJud', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1205089636, 'comment_body': 'Please add the license and a short description to every new file.
See e.g. `chat.rs` for an example.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 5, 25, 7, 11, 41, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MathJud', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1205110536, 'comment_body': "We should create a matrix specific `matrix.yml` config file, which is saved in qaul's default storage location, for that it is working as everything else in qaul.
The location to save the file to, can be asked from libqaul via the RPC debug>StoragePathRequest message. (see `rust/libqaul/src/rpc/debug.proto`)
If there is more matrix-bridge related stuff, i suggest to create an extra `matrix` folder in the qaul storage directory and use it as the storage directory for all matrix related stuff.
For saving and reading the configuration libqaul uses the crate `config`. (see `rust/libqaul/src/storage/configuration`.)", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 5, 25, 7, 32, 9, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MathJud', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1205139003, 'comment_body': 'please handle the returned result.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 5, 25, 7, 57, 52, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MathJud', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1213477787, 'comment_body': '@MathJud This is the place where I am interested in calling the rpc function from `users.rs`. 
Use case is that. In matrix room, a user sends a message `!users-list`. This should return the data which we will format with better strings. 

If we are successful to do just this, Next we can call the rpc function of `feed.rs` and that should allow us to send any messages which we write in qaul world to be sent over to the matrix room. And this should be enough to complete our first milestone.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 1, 17, 36, 43, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Harshil-Jani', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1214125705, 'comment_body': 'There are several ways to do that.

1) The bridge client queries regularly libqaul via RPC for a list of users, e.g. all 10 seconds. This list is stored in a way to be accessed by different threads and functions (see the state storage object https://crates.io/crates/state )

2) Create an asynchronous event system, where you pause your function until the next user list arrived.

As we anyway will need the user information, and also will need to query several other information regularly I would go with solution 1. It is also much simpler to implement.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 2, 9, 10, 46, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MathJud', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1214125958, 'comment_body': 'Which users do you want to deliver here?

a) all known users, independent if they are online or not (this is an ever growing list of users)
b) the users that are online at this time.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 2, 9, 11, 4, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MathJud', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1214247649, 'comment_body': "> Which users do you want to deliver here?
a) all known users, independent if they are online or not (this is an ever growing list of users)
b) the users that are online at this time.

It's (a)", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 6, 2, 11, 19, 45, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Harshil-Jani', 'type': 'User'}]
